<paragraph id="8BB336FB3227FFCD83E9FBBB2DB9FB51" blockId="24.[151,1437,1148,1499]" box="[151,402,1148,1174]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<heading id="D0FB81973227FFCD83E9FBBB2DB9FB51" box="[151,402,1148,1174]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" reason="5">
<taxonomicName id="4C0C4D783227FFCD83E9FBBB2DB9FB51" baseAuthorityName="Allen" baseAuthorityYear="1901" box="[151,402,1148,1174]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Hylaeamys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perenensis">
<emphasis id="B978EAE93227FFCD83E9FBBB2DB9FB51" box="[151,402,1148,1174]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Hylaeamys perenensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB336FB3227FFCD83B9FB662FCFFA54" blockId="24.[151,1437,1148,1499]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
Karyotype: 2n = 52 and FN = 62. Autosomal complement: six metacentric and submetacentric pairs medium to small decreasing in size, and 19 acrocentric pairs (one very large and the remaining large to small decreasing in size). Sex chromosomes: X, a large acrocentric; Y, a small acrocentric (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3227FFCD80A3FB2F28C0FAC5" author="Gardner, A. L. &amp; Patton, J. L." box="[989,1259,1256,1283]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="1 - 48" refId="ref67114" refString="Gardner, A. L. &amp; Patton, J. L. (1976) Karyotypic variation in Oryzomyine rodents (Cricetinae) with comments on chromosomal evolution in the Neotropical Cricetine complex. Occasional papers of the Museum of Zoology, 49, 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="1976">Gardner &amp; Patton 1976</bibRefCitation>
, pp. 6, 
<figureCitation id="13372A7E3227FFCD8641FB2F29B3FAC5" box="[1343,1432,1256,1282]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1191,1215]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,281,1162]" captionTargetId="figure-69@7.[151,1436,273,1168]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Distribution of diploid and fundamental number of karyotyped specimens of genus Cerradomys. (□) C. akroai; (■) C. goytaca; (ê) C. langguthi; (r) C. maracajuensis; (▲) C. marinhus; (○) C. scotti; (☆) C. subflavus; (l) C. vivoi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423619/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3227FFCD83E9FACA2D74FAE1" author="Patton, J. L. &amp; Silva, M. N. &amp; Malcolm, J. R." box="[151,351,1292,1319]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="1 - 306" refId="ref71077" refString="Patton, J. L., Silva, M. N. &amp; Malcolm, J. R. (2000) Mammals of the Rio Jurua and the evolutionary and ecological diversification of Amazonia. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 244, 1 - 306. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2000) 244 % 3 C 0001: MOTRJA % 3 E 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2000">
Patton 
<emphasis id="B978EAE93227FFCD839BFACA2D3DFAE1" box="[229,278,1292,1318]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">et al</emphasis>
. 2000
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3227FFCD8217FACB2E8BFAE1" author="Volobouev, V. T. &amp; Aniskin, V. M." box="[361,672,1292,1318]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="295 - 304" refId="ref74775" refString="Volobouev, V. T. &amp; Aniskin, V. M. (2000) Comparative chromosome banding analysis of three South American species of rice rats of the genus Oryzomys (Rodentia, Sigmodontinae). Chromosome Research, 8, 295 - 304. https: // doi. org / 10.1023 / A: 1009223210737" type="journal article" year="2000">Volobouev &amp; Aniskin 2000</bibRefCitation>
). C-banding metaphases exhibited blocks of constitutive heterochromatin on the pericentromeric region of all autosomes and on the X chromosome. The Y chromosome was entirely heterochromatic. G-banding was also performed (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3227FFCD81B8FA93282AFAA9" author="Volobouev, V. T. &amp; Aniskin, V. M." box="[710,1025,1364,1390]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="295 - 304" refId="ref74775" refString="Volobouev, V. T. &amp; Aniskin, V. M. (2000) Comparative chromosome banding analysis of three South American species of rice rats of the genus Oryzomys (Rodentia, Sigmodontinae). Chromosome Research, 8, 295 - 304. https: // doi. org / 10.1023 / A: 1009223210737" type="journal article" year="2000">Volobouev &amp; Aniskin 2000</bibRefCitation>
). A different fundamental number of 64 was reported by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3227FFCD820AFABE2E7BFA55" author="Musser, G. G. &amp; Carleton, M. D. &amp; Brothers, E. M. &amp; Gardner, A. L." box="[372,592,1400,1427]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="1 - 376" refId="ref69760" refString="Musser, G. G., Carleton, M. D., Brothers, E. M. &amp; Gardner, A. L. (1998) Systematic studies of Oryzomyine rodents (Muridae, Sigmodontinae): diagnoses and distributions of species formerly assigned to Oryzomys &quot; capito &quot;. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 236, 1 - 376." type="journal article" year="1998">
Musser 
<emphasis id="B978EAE93227FFCD82B3FABE2DD4FA55" box="[461,511,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">et al</emphasis>
. (1998
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3227FFCD8122FABF2ED1FA55" author="Malygin, V. M. &amp; Aniskin, V. M. &amp; Isaev, S. I. &amp; Milishnikov, A. N." box="[604,762,1400,1426]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="195 - 208" refId="ref69187" refString="Malygin, V. M., Aniskin, V. M., Isaev, S. I. &amp; Milishnikov, A. N. (1994) Amphinectomys savamis Malygin gen. Et sp. n., a new genus and a new species of water rat (Cricetidae, Rodentia) from Peruvian Amazonia. Zoologicheskii zhurnal, 73 (7 &amp; 8), 195 - 208." type="journal article" year="1994">Malygin 1994</bibRefCitation>
(congress abstract)).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31665703227FFCD83B9FA5B2F5AFA1C" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB336FB3227FFCD83B9FA5B2F5AFA1C" blockId="24.[151,1437,1148,1499]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
The karyotype of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0C4D783227FFCD82EFFA5A2E22FA71" baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[401,521,1437,1462]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Hylaeamys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oniscus">
<emphasis id="B978EAE93227FFCD82EFFA5A2E22FA71" box="[401,521,1437,1462]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">H. oniscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C0C4D783227FFCD813FFA5A2EF0FA71" baseAuthorityName="Allen" baseAuthorityYear="1901" box="[577,731,1437,1462]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Hylaeamys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perenensis">
<emphasis id="B978EAE93227FFCD813FFA5A2EF0FA71" box="[577,731,1437,1462]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">H. perenensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were very similar, however 
<taxonomicName id="4C0C4D783227FFCD8760FA5A2893FA71" baseAuthorityName="Allen" baseAuthorityYear="1901" box="[1054,1208,1437,1462]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Hylaeamys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perenensis">
<emphasis id="B978EAE93227FFCD8760FA5A2893FA71" box="[1054,1208,1437,1462]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">H. perenensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exhibits a distinctly large acrocentric chromosome that was not present in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0C4D783227FFCD818AFA062F41FA1D" baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[756,874,1473,1498]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Hylaeamys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oniscus">
<emphasis id="B978EAE93227FFCD818AFA062F41FA1D" box="[756,874,1473,1498]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">H. oniscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
